title: CATER 155520, Kly Mod 14-5: trips off with thyratron temp + control power interlocks off.
text: Kly Mod 14-5: discovered K6 relay had solenoid wires with missing insulation and the relay frame corroded and burned around wiring with missing insulation. Rapped on K6 several times: sure enough, this action caused K32 relay (thyratron temp + control power) to de-energize. Bare wire was intermittently touching grounded frame of relay. Replaced K6 with relay from spare mod next to 14-4. Also, since there was some corrosion on K32, replaced it with K32 from spare mod next to 14-5. After 55 min time in, station back on. Rapped on K6 several times with screwdriver: K32 remains energized. Mod running stably. CATER ready to close.

title: starting energy change
Still seeing no beam in LI12 and beyond
text: We don't see anything on any SCP or EPICS BPMs, and there is nothing on the PR14803 profile monitor when we insert it, so it seems like we are losing the beam in 12. This could just be a consequence of none of the stations in 12 contributing to the beam. Ryan also suggested that the LI11 steering feedback could have gotten itself into a weird state (possibly because the LI12 Micro went down) and it could be steering the beam into the wall. We are not able to turn off the LI11 feedback using the instructions in the wiki (https://aosd.slac.stanford.edu/wiki/index.php/FACET_LI11_Steering_Feedback). We get the following error: "IPL in progress. Cold starting will allow you to interfere."

We have (actually good) beam again! Mystery solved! Details inside.
text: Talked to Ryan, he said we can set 10-2 back up to SFB ADES=10. We expect to not get trips during the day, and were probably getting so many since it was so cold overnight. I mentioned that we had very poor transmission, despite being on energy and steering to the reference orbit. Ryan also said that some of those quads in the W chicane area have been OOT for a long time. We discovered that SYAG was actually in the beam, but Ahmed and I had been deceived by the false "OUT" status on FACET Home Profile Monitor/LI20. I pulled SYAG (for real this time), and we are back to 75ish% transmission to dump. These garbage statuses have been CATERed (155545).

Claims to be near 0 now in both planes BUT... the high TMIT and the hugely jumpy orbit in LI19 makes me wonder if we are actually far from 0 here and bouncing the beam off of this quad. The previous corrector currently has be on a bit strong to reach this "0" value. LI20 2050 - low TMIT is odd, but I just did some more tests and I think the x readout is legitimate. (I had previously wondered why being on energy reduced transmission - but looking at a difference orbit, getting on energy messed up the orbit in the W chicane. Maybe the energy had drifted while someone was steering?) LI20 3156 - reads no TMIT and large negative positions? Hard to say if this is wrong though, since the W chicane orbit can be ugly sometimes.

Maybe the energy had drifted while someone was steering?) LI20 2360 - said "X BAD" and didn't seem to respond to correctors at one point, although seems to have fixed itself since then. LI20 3156 - reads no TMIT and large negative positions? Hard to say if this is wrong though, since the W chicane orbit can be ugly sometimes.

title: Working on improving transmission to the dump, so far about 75%
Day shift summary
text: At the beginning of day shift, the beam was parked on TD-11 with the gun at a lower amplitude (9.5MW instead of 10MW) to recover from slew of peak power faults over owl shift. After consulting with FACET physicists they determined it was okay to ramp up the gun to 10MW and continue with the program. A large portion of the rest of the shift until about 14:11 was spent trying to recover the beam transmission from the beginning of owl shift. We were also chasing problems such as quads tripping off (Q2E specifically), and a phase jump in L3. We spent some time phasing L3 to recover some of the lost transmission. It seems like we've recovered about 75% transmission to the dump, and we are spending the rest of the time further optimizing the transmission, and trying to get the beam position/shape right on DT0TR2 so we can start doing chirp scans.
